WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.800
Hi everybody, can you hear me okay? Awesome. Okay, my name is Keegan, and today I'm going

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:13.400
to talk to you about building feature-full, user-friendly interactive data explorers with

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:21.200
Shiny and friends. So, let's talk about Shiny. This is a Shiny app. This Shiny app presents

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:26.540
data on the number of crimes in different cities. This Shiny app has multiple ways to

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:32.779
explore the data, including a data table, an interactive map, and a line chart. This

00:00:32.779 --> 00:00:39.700
Shiny app also has filters to let users select a specific day or type of crime. This Shiny

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:48.220
app brings data to a user and lets them explore it in an interactive way. It's a data explorer.

00:00:48.220 --> 00:00:53.740
This is also a Shiny app. This Shiny app has a homepage that describes the data that are

00:00:53.740 --> 00:01:00.040
contained in the Shiny app site. It has details about different ways that users can explore

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:06.580
the data and encourages them to go find the data in a way that works for them. This Shiny

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:12.720
app has multiple ways to explore data. There are interactive data tables that let users

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:18.500
filter to a specific date or type of crime. There are details when a user is focused on

00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:23.820
a specific piece of the data. And there are multiple ways to explore the data in this

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:33.739
Shiny app, including an interactive table, an interactive map, and interactive line charts.

00:01:33.739 --> 00:01:38.860
This Shiny app also provides detailed information to users when they make certain selections.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:42.580
So if they pick a specific city, there are details about where that city's data are coming

00:01:42.580 --> 00:01:47.059
from. If they pick a certain type of crime, there are details about how we define that

00:01:47.059 --> 00:01:51.459
type of crime and where that data are coming from.

00:01:51.459 --> 00:01:57.260
So today, I want to talk to you about how you can get from a Shiny app to a Shiny app.

00:01:57.260 --> 00:02:01.959
And by that, I mean, how can we get from a basic Shiny app that brings data to your users

00:02:01.959 --> 00:02:07.540
to a full data explorer experience that really invites users in, tells them what the data

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:11.940
are, how they can explore them, and provides the right context and details along their

00:02:11.940 --> 00:02:19.979
data exploration journey. And to do this, you should ask yourself, can Shiny do that?

00:02:19.979 --> 00:02:25.339
What do I mean by this question? Well, let's look at an example. Let's first ask ourselves,

00:02:25.339 --> 00:02:32.419
can Shiny look and feel like a full website? So let's start with our basic Shiny app. The

00:02:32.419 --> 00:02:36.699
users plopped right into this data table. And to most of us who are pretty used to working

00:02:36.699 --> 00:02:41.419
with data, it might be clear right away how to interact with this data. But there's still

00:02:41.419 --> 00:02:47.139
probably lots of questions about where the data come from and what limitations they might have.

00:02:47.139 --> 00:02:51.899
So let's give our users a home page. Let's give them somewhere to land. Let's welcome

00:02:51.899 --> 00:02:56.779
them into the data explorer, tell them where the data are coming from, show them the different

00:02:56.779 --> 00:03:02.220
ways they can explore the data, and give them options for learning more about this data

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:07.300
explorer, including learning more about the data sources or who built the site and why

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:14.820
they built the site. We can also add additional context like about and methodology pages that

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:19.300
just answer frequently asked questions users might have about the data in this site, like

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:24.139
what is the purpose? Why am I here? What are the limitations of the tool or the data in

00:03:24.139 --> 00:03:28.940
the tool? And who should I contact if I have questions about the data in this explorer

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:35.940
or how to use it? So by just adding really a couple of pages to our Shiny app and not

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:41.059
a lot of content really, we've given our users a lot more context for the data in the

00:03:41.059 --> 00:03:47.699
app and how to use it. So it already feels a little more like a full website. But let's

00:03:47.699 --> 00:03:53.240
take this a step further. The default operations of Shiny is that it kind of functions like

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:57.820
a single page application, right? You move between different tabs, but you're really

00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:03.139
never leaving the same page. With actually just a few lines of code in the server, we

00:04:03.139 --> 00:04:07.860
can add sub URLs for each of our pages to help our users move to different sections

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:15.619
of our app through either the navigation or through the URL. We can also have these changes

00:04:15.619 --> 00:04:20.100
logged in the browser so that users can use forward and back buttons in the browser to

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:25.579
track their own journey. This might feel like a really small thing, but this actually has

00:04:25.579 --> 00:04:30.339
a really big impact on users feeling like they're on a full website. Usually when you're

00:04:30.339 --> 00:04:34.019
on a website, you expect that you can move back and forth between the actions that you

00:04:34.019 --> 00:04:39.220
take. This is something we maybe take for granted. And then in a Shiny app, you might

00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:45.140
ask the question, wait, what page was I just on? So if you add these little details to

00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:50.540
make your data explorer feel a little bit more like a full website, you'll help your

00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:58.940
users explore more effectively and feel like they're on a full website. Okay. So what else

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:05.380
can Shiny do? Let's ask, can Shiny customize and explain a user's experience as they explore

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:13.500
data? Let's first think about providing some context. So here we've got a title. This title

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:18.640
describes the data someone's looking at in this filtered data table. But we can also

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:24.040
really easily change this title reactively based on our user selection. Again, this feels

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:28.820
like a really small detail. This doesn't take a lot of effort, but now we're really making

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:33.820
it very clear exactly what data a user's looking at at any given point in time. It's

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:38.040
right there, right in front of their face. Again, for those of us who are used to exploring

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:42.700
data with Shiny apps, it's pretty clear that we're looking at aggravated assaults on July

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:48.660
9th. But for those who aren't necessarily used to how a data exploration tool works,

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:52.859
reinforcing it with a big title that changes along with them provides them the context

00:05:52.859 --> 00:05:59.579
for exactly what they're looking at. We can also do this with detailed notes. So we can

00:05:59.579 --> 00:06:05.739
add context that answers questions users might have when they navigate to a specific view.

00:06:05.739 --> 00:06:10.940
We can add the definition of different crime types, for example, in this case, so that

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:15.059
when a user's looking at a specific view, an initial question they might have about

00:06:15.059 --> 00:06:20.940
the data they're looking at, how do we define aggravated assault or larceny, is right there.

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:24.940
We haven't inundated them with all of the information about all of the different crime

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:29.339
types. We're showing them what they need, when they need to see it. So we're providing

00:06:29.339 --> 00:06:37.779
them the right context to learn about what they're exploring as they explore it.

00:06:37.779 --> 00:06:41.859
So now let's say our user in this app finds something they're interested in. Let's say

00:06:41.859 --> 00:06:48.420
they're really fascinated by burglaries on July 30th. Using Shiny bookmarking, we can

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:54.739
actually let users store the state of an app, save that in a URL, and if they take

00:06:54.739 --> 00:06:59.500
that URL and put it into their browser, it brings us right back to where we were. This

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:05.700
might be a slightly unconventional way of using bookmarking, but it's really nice because

00:07:05.700 --> 00:07:10.899
we can let users find a specific insight as they explore data, save that for later, and

00:07:10.899 --> 00:07:18.179
come back to it or share it with others. So again, by just making a few small changes,

00:07:18.179 --> 00:07:23.019
we've made the journey of exploring this data a lot more understandable for our users,

00:07:23.019 --> 00:07:28.739
and we've given them a lot more power to actually share what they find with other people.

00:07:28.739 --> 00:07:34.500
So to go from this to the site I was showing you before obviously takes a little bit more

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:39.779
time and energy than that. And unfortunately, I can't teach you how to do all of this today.

00:07:39.779 --> 00:07:44.940
But I do think, you know, if you learn some CSS, you're kind of on your way. But what

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:49.140
I really want you to take away from this is think about what your users might want

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:54.739
to learn. Think about what questions they might have about the data. And then ask yourself,

00:07:54.739 --> 00:07:59.179
can Shiny do that? Instead of thinking, I can just toss this data in a Shiny app and

00:07:59.179 --> 00:08:03.540
share it with people. If you flip the way you think about the question and instead ask

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:08.500
if Shiny can do a thing you want to do, most of the time the answer is going to be yes.

00:08:08.500 --> 00:08:14.339
And you can have a lot more of a rich experience for your users.

00:08:14.339 --> 00:08:19.339
So at this point, you might be asking, why should I use Shiny to do that? And there are

00:08:19.339 --> 00:08:25.299
two pieces to this question. The first is, why should I do that? And the second is, why

00:08:25.299 --> 00:08:31.619
should I use Shiny for it? So the first question, why should I do that? For me, the answer is

00:08:31.619 --> 00:08:36.739
pretty simple. It's part of my job. So I work at NORC at the University of Chicago, which

00:08:36.739 --> 00:08:41.739
is a nonprofit research institution. And our main tagline is that we deliver objective,

00:08:41.739 --> 00:08:46.460
nonpartisan insights and analysis that decision makers trust. So what this means for me as

00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:51.460
a statistician is I'm generally working with data that my colleagues in public health or

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:58.500
health care or education research have collected or collated or analyzed in some way. And I'm

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:05.500
trying to bring that data to an audience that can use it to make important decisions.

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:10.940
So what that might mean is helping communicate crime data from different cities that update

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:16.340
daily to understand where there are gaps in open crime data or compare crime rates between

00:09:16.340 --> 00:09:22.619
different cities of different types. Or this might mean helping share data from the Medicare

00:09:22.619 --> 00:09:27.340
Current Beneficiary Survey to better understand the Medicare population and their needs and

00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:32.679
their access to health care. Or it might mean sharing data on the population of lawyers

00:09:32.679 --> 00:09:36.960
in Massachusetts, their demographics and information about their law practices to better

00:09:36.960 --> 00:09:43.039
understand that community and their changes over time. So bringing data to an audience

00:09:43.039 --> 00:09:46.799
and helping them learn about that data and helping them make informed insights from that

00:09:46.799 --> 00:09:53.080
data is a huge part of what I do. So why should we take the time and energy to make these

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:59.159
sites into full explorers that really help our users learn and share this information?

00:09:59.159 --> 00:10:03.479
Here is your data user. If you plop them into a site and show them data and let them

00:10:03.479 --> 00:10:08.400
explore it, they might have a lot of questions. They might not understand what they're doing

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:13.640
on the site, how the data got there, or what they can do with the information. If we give

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:18.159
them one of those landing pages that tell them what data are on the site and how they

00:10:18.159 --> 00:10:25.280
can explore it, they're going to be drawn in to the site and curious to explore more.

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:29.919
If we provide them the right context by providing methodology and about pages, then our user

00:10:29.919 --> 00:10:35.719
has a better understanding of where the data come from. If we provide those customized

00:10:35.719 --> 00:10:40.479
labels and contexts for our users as they explore on their data exploration journey,

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:43.799
they're going to better understand what a specific view or a specific data point is

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:49.960
showing them. If we give people multiple ways to explore the data, they can bring their

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:54.599
own research questions, find meaningful patterns that might impact a decision they have to

00:10:54.599 --> 00:11:00.559
make or something they want to learn about a specific data set. And if we give them ways

00:11:00.559 --> 00:11:05.000
to share and learn, they can translate what they've learned from exploring this data into

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:13.880
impactful insights and action. Yay! Thanks for laughing, everyone. Okay. So why should

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:18.119
I use Shiny to do this? This is the other big question. Besides the fact that it's just

00:11:18.119 --> 00:11:22.559
fun, there are practical reasons that it's really effective to use Shiny to do these

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:27.200
things. So to build a full data explorer like this, you would typically need three

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:32.200
types of skill sets. You would need somebody who understands the data structure. That might

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:36.559
be your statisticians or data scientists who know the variables in the data, know how it's

00:11:36.559 --> 00:11:41.919
structured, know how to wrangle the data. You need somebody to build the interface.

00:11:41.919 --> 00:11:46.119
That would be your front-end developers. They can actually build out the components that

00:11:46.119 --> 00:11:51.799
are going to be used by your users. Then you need people to connect the data and the interface

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:56.640
together. That would typically be your back-end developers. You might be able to see where

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:02.599
this is going. When we use Shiny, we can smash all of these skill sets into one group of

00:12:02.599 --> 00:12:08.159
people, and that is Shiny developers who can build the whole thing from start to finish.

00:12:08.159 --> 00:12:16.599
So when we're able to have all these skill sets in Shiny developers who understand data,

00:12:16.599 --> 00:12:21.119
understand how to program and use statistical programming software, and then they can learn

00:12:21.159 --> 00:12:26.119
how to build the user interface and server components in Shiny, we've condensed the sets

00:12:26.119 --> 00:12:31.679
of skills that we need into one smaller group. This means we can expand our group to enhance

00:12:31.679 --> 00:12:36.679
our users' experience and get the most out of data exploration. We can work with subject

00:12:36.679 --> 00:12:41.599
matter experts who understand the data at hand, who an audience member might be that's

00:12:41.599 --> 00:12:46.200
going to use and explore this data, and what type of research questions those people might

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:52.039
have. We can also work with communication specialists who know how to best communicate

00:12:52.039 --> 00:12:59.359
with an audience and connect with an audience, and how to improve the journey of a user throughout

00:12:59.359 --> 00:13:05.539
the site. So you probably won't be surprised to learn that the group of people who built

00:13:05.539 --> 00:13:10.840
the crime site I was showing you looks a lot like this. We had subject matter experts in

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:15.760
crime data and crime data policy who helped us understand the purpose and the goals of

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:21.280
the site. We had our Shiny developer team who built the whole thing, and we had our

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:25.679
communication specialists who helped us think through the user experience and communicating

00:13:25.679 --> 00:13:29.799
most effectively with our audience. And the communication specialists are really, really

00:13:29.799 --> 00:13:37.320
great about asking the question, can Shiny do this? So very helpful people to have around.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:40.840
So when you have all of these different sets of skills, the people who know the point of

00:13:40.840 --> 00:13:45.400
the data and who's going to use it, the people who can build the whole thing, and the people

00:13:45.440 --> 00:13:51.359
who can help communicate it effectively, now you can build full data explorer sites. You

00:13:51.359 --> 00:13:57.000
can communicate effectively with your audience, help them learn from the data, explore it,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:03.119
have the right context as they explore, and take what they've learned and share those

00:14:03.119 --> 00:14:08.719
insights and turn them into action. And the really cool part about this is if you think

00:14:08.719 --> 00:14:14.840
about this from the perspective of can Shiny do that, you end up building sites that maybe

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:20.919
don't look or feel like Shiny, and you get lots of people asking, wait, that's Shiny?

00:14:20.919 --> 00:14:25.440
And you get to say, yes, yes, it is. Thank you.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:40.400
Thank you so much, Keegan. I do have a few questions from our virtual audience. So one

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:45.559
is a little bit of a technical question regarding the sub URLs. Do you need a separate package

00:14:45.559 --> 00:14:47.760
to do that? Or can you do that with Base Shiny?

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:49.760
Nope, Base Shiny.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:57.080
Great. So is the source of the app shown in the slides available?

00:14:57.080 --> 00:14:58.080
Or do you have...

